			<div id = "comment-9337" class = "comment">
				<p>Ah, ok. Steering is not based on how the wheel itself is actuated, it's based on how the wheels, and how many wheels, contribute to the vehicle turning.</p>
			</div>
			<div id = "comment-9339" class = "comment">
				<p>Correct. Akerman came around to solve a ratio problem (the angle is not the same for both wheels). But this is just doing it electrically instead of mechanically. And it can even consider all 4 corners as well :)</p>
			</div>
			<div id = "comment-9389" class = "comment">
				<p>I believe that "Ackerman" refers only to the mechanism that's used in cars.  There is no other way to steer (without skidding) than by aligning all the wheels toward the same point.</p>
			</div>
			<div id = "comment-9391" class = "comment">
				<p>Yes, I agree. The mars rocker bogie mimics mechanical ackerman electrically, and at all corners. I didn't want to confuse a simplistic explanation. And it is actually not aligned to the same point, it represents the best slip angle of two different diameter circles as far as I know.</p>
			</div>
